++++?!\"*$\"\"%\"\"!" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "sub
s(x=0,D1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"$G\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 23 "-The y intercept is 128" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 32 "-The x intercepts are at 2 and 4" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 54 "-D1 is positive (- infinity to 2, and 4 to + infinity)" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 24 "-D1 is negative (2 to 4)" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 268 "" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 0 21 21 "Note on end l
imits:  " }}{PARA 267 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 54 "        d1 tends to +infini
ty as x tends to + infinity" }}{PARA 269 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 53 "        \+
d1 tends to +infinity as x tends to -infinity" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Polynomials:  Local extreme values \+
and monotonicity.  Beyond information of the type gathered above about
 intercepts and signs of a polynomial,  other important information ca
n be determined from the so called \"critical points\" of a polynomial
.  The critical points of a polynomial are the intercepts of its deriv
ative.  Since the derivative of a function at a point represents the s
lope of the tangent line to the graph of the that function at the poin
t, then the intercepts of the derivative are places where the the tang
ent lines to the function are flat, i.e., are horizontal lines.  At su
ch places the graph is neither increasing nor decreasing.  Elsewhere t
he graph must be either increasing or decreasing.  For a polynomial, l
ocal extreme values (local maximums or local minimums) must occur at t
he intercepts of the derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing features are important \+
in analyzing the graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical points of the fun
ction" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "                      For a poly
nomial these are the intercepts of the derivative of the polynomial" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g.    local maximum points of the g
raph of a function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "         \+
             These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for w
hich the y-value is locally the largest value of the function.  Nearby
 values on the graph are lower.  For a polynomials the x-value of the \+
point (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of the graph of a fun
ction y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "                     \+
 These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which the y-v
alue is locally the smallest value of the function.  Nearby values on \+
the graph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,y
) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 108 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the func
tion where the values of the function are increasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions where the graph r
ises as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For a continuous f
unction, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded \+
by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 257 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     j.    regions (intervals) in the domain of t
he function where the values of the function are decreasing" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions where the
 graph falls as the graph is traversed from left to right.  For a cont
inuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are \+
bounded by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 275 "For each
 of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.  Ch
oose a range that will optimally represent the features of the graph. \+
 Include the graph of the deriviative of the polynomial on the plot.  \+
 Plot the function in red and the derviative in green.   " }{TEXT 269 
4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 89 ", for each polynomial find each of the above te
n graphcial characteristics (a.  thru j.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = x^2-2*
x-15;" "6#/%\"yG,(*$%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"*&F(F)F'F)!\"\"\"#:F+" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "A2:=x^2-2*x-15;\n" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#A2G,(*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F**&F)F*F(F*!\"\"\"#:F," 
